00:14:58,162 --> 00:15:00,596
Mr. Ward, this one right here
ain't gonna make it.

258
00:15:00,598 --> 00:15:02,532
[ laughing ] Shh.

259
00:15:04,067 --> 00:15:05,835
Here! Rock!

260
00:15:08,672 --> 00:15:10,139
Heel.

261
00:15:14,077 --> 00:15:16,879
Christmas, um,

262
00:15:16,881 --> 00:15:20,883
have the skiff at Broad
quarter past 3:00 and...

263
00:15:22,085 --> 00:15:24,220
keep the bird
for supper.

264
00:15:24,222 --> 00:15:25,588
All right, then.

265
00:15:25,590 --> 00:15:27,557
Evening, Mr. Ward.

266
00:15:29,726 --> 00:15:31,460
Here!

267
00:15:42,873 --> 00:15:45,474
[ lively piano and boisterous
voices inside bar ]

268
00:15:48,211 --> 00:15:49,946
WARD:
That wasn't a hug!

269
00:15:49,948 --> 00:15:51,914
I better go now.

270
00:15:53,917 --> 00:15:56,485
Hey! Come on!

271
00:15:56,487 --> 00:15:58,487
♪ I'm a Yankee Doodle,
why? ♪

272
00:15:58,489 --> 00:16:01,624
♪ I report back
to Uncle Sam ♪

273
00:16:01,626 --> 00:16:04,527
♪ So I can't shoot birds
out the sky ♪

274
00:16:05,329 --> 00:16:06,329
[ groans ]

275
00:16:06,331 --> 00:16:10,166
[ watch ticking ]

276
00:16:11,535 --> 00:16:14,036
Oh! Rock!

277
00:16:14,038 --> 00:16:15,838
[ dog whines ]

278
00:16:18,241 --> 00:16:19,675
Come on.

279
00:16:21,178 --> 00:16:22,745
Good boy.

280
00:16:35,292 --> 00:16:38,661
[ gunshots ]

281
00:16:51,842 --> 00:16:54,543
WARD: I'm certain you
could shoot as many as me

282
00:16:54,545 --> 00:16:56,846
if you give up
your aversion to gloves.

283
00:16:56,848 --> 00:16:58,614
[ laughing ]

284
00:17:00,017 --> 00:17:01,751
I get 36.

285
00:17:05,689 --> 00:17:08,024
Order was 39.

286
00:17:08,026 --> 00:17:11,260
We got 39.

287
00:17:11,262 --> 00:17:13,896
Fine.
I count again.

288
00:17:13,898 --> 00:17:17,066
All right, let's say
we shot the same number

289
00:17:17,068 --> 00:17:20,336
and leave the unlikely
metaphysical ramification

290
00:17:20,338 --> 00:17:21,837
of such a fact
for another day.

291
00:17:21,839 --> 00:17:23,272
Well, all right then.

292
00:17:23,274 --> 00:17:24,474
You just keep
carrying me,

293
00:17:24,475 --> 00:17:26,142
I keep carrying
your duck.

294
00:17:31,314 --> 00:17:32,815
There you are.

295
00:17:35,419 --> 00:17:37,153
[ dog moans ]

296
00:17:40,524 --> 00:17:43,759
$61.50.

297
00:17:47,297 --> 00:17:49,565
Uh, pardon me,
mademoiselle,

298
00:17:49,567 --> 00:17:52,034
I, uh, hope
he didn't disturb you.

299
00:17:52,036 --> 00:17:53,369
[ dog barks
and shakes ]

300
00:17:53,371 --> 00:17:55,938
[ laughs ]
No. He's delightful.

301
00:17:55,940 --> 00:17:59,975
Well, just the same,
he's not to leave me,

302
00:17:59,977 --> 00:18:02,044
by arrangement
of the management.

303
00:18:02,046 --> 00:18:03,979
You see, he doesn't
really belong in here.

304
00:18:03,981 --> 00:18:06,982
Well, the same could
be said for those boots.

305
00:18:06,984 --> 00:18:12,321
Oh, these boots are
somewhat less headstrong.

306
00:18:12,323 --> 00:18:15,291
They, uh,
stay better to heel.

307
00:18:17,194 --> 00:18:19,495
Lucy, we're ready.

308
00:18:19,497 --> 00:18:23,833
Well, now it's my turn
to be called to heel.

309
00:18:25,969 --> 00:18:28,170
DESK CLERK
Mr. Allen, your money.

310
00:18:30,907 --> 00:18:33,542
Excuse me.
Are you Mr. Ward Allen?

311
00:18:33,544 --> 00:18:35,711
WARD: Yes, I am.

312
00:18:35,713 --> 00:18:37,313
Have we met?

313
00:18:37,315 --> 00:18:39,749
Well, let's just say
I've met your reputation,

314
00:18:39,751 --> 00:18:41,383
far and wide, in fact.

315
00:18:41,385 --> 00:18:43,085
Lies substantially.

316
00:18:43,087 --> 00:18:45,888
Oh, so you aren't the best guide
on the river then.

317
00:18:45,890 --> 00:18:47,456
WARD: No,
I'm no guide at all.

318
00:18:47,458 --> 00:18:48,891
I am a market hunter.

319
00:18:48,893 --> 00:18:50,093
Yes, you're the one.

320
00:18:50,094 --> 00:18:51,761
I happen to have
a house guest,

321
00:18:51,763 --> 00:18:53,329
a gentleman
from Virginia.

322
00:18:53,331 --> 00:18:55,698
He's the son
of Sir Stuart Graham,

323
00:18:55,700 --> 00:18:56,866
close friend
and colleague,

324
00:18:56,868 --> 00:18:58,801
and he'd like
to hunt our river.

325
00:18:58,803 --> 00:19:02,271
Well, any fool
can find it for him.

326
00:19:02,273 --> 00:19:04,340
[ Lucy laughs ]

327
00:19:06,576 --> 00:19:07,977
I'm not looking
for just any fool.

328
00:19:07,979 --> 00:19:09,912
I'm looking
for the best fool going,

329
00:19:09,914 --> 00:19:11,647
and they say that's you.
Is it?

330
00:19:13,116 --> 00:19:14,750
A day as a guide

331
00:19:14,752 --> 00:19:17,853
is a significant loss
of production from my end.

332
00:19:17,855 --> 00:19:19,855
Oh, money's no object.

333
00:19:25,428 --> 00:19:27,096
All right,

334
00:19:27,098 --> 00:19:29,999
but no one
touches my guns...

335
00:19:31,134 --> 00:19:32,334
or my dog.

336
00:19:32,336 --> 00:19:34,203
MR. STUBBS: Splendid.
Then we have a deal.

337
00:19:34,205 --> 00:19:36,272
Your gesture
is deeply appreciated,

338
00:19:36,274 --> 00:19:40,176
and I assure you, Mr. Graham
will come well-equipped.

339
00:19:41,178 --> 00:19:42,778
Careful.

340
00:19:42,780 --> 00:19:46,148
That bag was a gift
from the Governor of Virginia.

341
00:19:46,150 --> 00:19:49,385
Well, then it should
hold up just fine.

342
00:19:53,490 --> 00:19:55,991
[ duck call ]

343
00:19:59,095 --> 00:20:01,630
I don't know how you
do this in, uh, Virginia,

344
00:20:01,632 --> 00:20:04,466
but here, we prefer
to come unannounced.

345
00:20:06,269 --> 00:20:09,338
I assure you,
I've hunted India, Africa.

346
00:20:09,340 --> 00:20:10,773
My steady companion...

347
00:20:10,775 --> 00:20:12,308
Are you here to hunt,

348
00:20:12,310 --> 00:20:14,844
or to impress the dog
with your pedigree, Mr. Graham?

349
00:20:17,314 --> 00:20:21,617
If my sources are correct,
and I'm sure they are,

350
00:20:21,619 --> 00:20:24,353
you're a bit
of a paradox, Mr. Allen.

351
00:20:24,355 --> 00:20:26,155
You were educated abroad,

352
00:20:26,157 --> 00:20:29,425
at my alma mater,
Oxford, in fact.

353
00:20:29,427 --> 00:20:32,394
Known as Buffalo Bill,

354
00:20:32,396 --> 00:20:33,929
yet you
are the descendent

355
00:20:33,931 --> 00:20:37,733
and sole inheritor
of the Allen plantation.

356
00:20:40,904 --> 00:20:44,340
I'm, uh, but a laborer.

357
00:20:44,342 --> 00:20:47,376
I earn that I eat,
get that I wear...

358
00:20:48,411 --> 00:20:50,346
owe no man hate,

359
00:20:50,348 --> 00:20:52,481
envy no man's happiness.

360
00:20:55,619 --> 00:20:56,986
Content...

361
00:20:58,221 --> 00:21:00,122
with my harm.

362
00:21:02,392 --> 00:21:04,260
Truly
of the manor born,

363
00:21:04,262 --> 00:21:08,130
and yet you choose a Negro
as your steady companion.

364
00:21:08,132 --> 00:21:11,133
No wonder Mr. Stubbs
sent all the way to Virginia

365
00:21:11,135 --> 00:21:13,435
to find a suitor
for his daughter.

366
00:21:14,638 --> 00:21:16,805
[ barking ]

367
00:21:17,741 --> 00:21:19,108
Get out.

368
00:21:19,110 --> 00:21:21,777
I'll do no such thing!

369
00:21:21,779 --> 00:21:23,145
[ bang ]

370
00:21:23,147 --> 00:21:26,282
I promised Miss Stubbs
a fresh bird for her table.

371
00:21:26,284 --> 00:21:29,885
It is your job to ensure
that I keep that promise.

372
00:21:29,887 --> 00:21:32,454
May I remind you
that you are a paid guide?

373
00:21:32,456 --> 00:21:33,756
[ cocks hammer ]

374
00:21:33,758 --> 00:21:35,157
No good hunter
takes a shot

375
00:21:35,159 --> 00:21:37,493
unless he knows
he can't miss.

376
00:21:37,495 --> 00:21:38,861
Get out.

377
00:21:38,863 --> 00:21:42,364
You have not heard
the last of this.

378
00:21:52,575 --> 00:21:55,678
CHRISTMAS: You likely stirred up trouble
now with Mr. Stubbs.

379
00:21:55,680 --> 00:21:57,046
[ Ward laughs ]

380
00:21:57,048 --> 00:21:59,648
Don't you have a cousin
that cooks for Stubbs?

381
00:21:59,650 --> 00:22:01,383
Not saying I don't,

382
00:22:01,385 --> 00:22:03,285
but she'd never talk about nothin'
wasn't her business.

383
00:22:03,287 --> 00:22:05,220
That's right.
You, either.

384
00:22:05,222 --> 00:22:07,323
That's right.
[ dog barking ]

385
00:22:07,325 --> 00:22:09,358
That's why you wouldn't know
nothin' about Stubbs' daughter.

386
00:22:09,360 --> 00:22:11,961
CHRISTMAS: The one that
turned down Lynah's boy?

387
00:22:11,963 --> 00:22:13,796
WARD: Which your cousin
never told you about.

388
00:22:13,798 --> 00:22:15,597
CHRISTMAS: Exactly.

389
00:22:19,202 --> 00:22:21,036
WARD: Well, look at that.

390
00:22:21,038 --> 00:22:22,972
Doodly Do
found his way home.

391
00:22:22,974 --> 00:22:26,175
Now, sir,
account for yourself.

392
00:22:27,744 --> 00:22:30,079
Evening, Mr. Sheriff,
Mr. Stubbs.

393
00:22:30,081 --> 00:22:31,480
We had a deal, Allen.

394
00:22:33,616 --> 00:22:35,384
Yes, we did.

395
00:22:35,386 --> 00:22:38,454
To take a gentleman
on the river.

396
00:22:38,456 --> 00:22:42,091
However, Mr. Graham proved
to be no gentleman at all.

397
00:22:42,093 --> 00:22:45,394
See, I feared he'd bring
embarrassment to you

398
00:22:45,396 --> 00:22:46,729
and your lovely family,

399
00:22:46,731 --> 00:22:48,030
boasting as it were

400
00:22:48,032 --> 00:22:50,699
over his intentions
towards your daughter.

401
00:22:50,701 --> 00:22:54,036
I... I... I resolutely refused

402
00:22:54,038 --> 00:22:55,938
to take a cent
of your money, sir.

403
00:22:55,940 --> 00:22:58,073
Please, if you will...

404
00:22:58,075 --> 00:23:01,810
Um, if I had exercised
my better judgment,

405
00:23:01,812 --> 00:23:03,846
you would
not have been exposed

406
00:23:03,848 --> 00:23:05,447
to this
public embarrassment.

407
00:23:05,449 --> 00:23:06,782
MR. STUBBS:
Well, appreciate that.

408
00:23:06,784 --> 00:23:07,983
I'd be pleased
if you'd take

409
00:23:07,985 --> 00:23:10,986
a pair of mallards
for your table.

410
00:23:15,492 --> 00:23:19,661
Well, our cook does do
wonders with waterfowl.

411
00:23:20,930 --> 00:23:22,664
First thing
in the morning, then.

412
00:23:22,666 --> 00:23:24,600
DRIVER: Hyah! Hyah!

413
00:23:32,609 --> 00:23:33,809
Quack quack quack.

414
00:23:40,583 --> 00:23:41,783
[ knocking ]

415
00:23:45,488 --> 00:23:47,289
[ door opens ]

416
00:23:47,291 --> 00:23:49,358
Mr. Allen.

417
00:23:49,360 --> 00:23:52,227
What happy accident
brings you here?

418
00:23:52,229 --> 00:23:56,799
Um, I promised your father
some fresh duck.

419
00:23:56,801 --> 00:23:58,133
Oh, well.

420
00:23:58,135 --> 00:23:59,835
A promise well kept, I see.
[ dog barks ]

421
00:23:59,837 --> 00:24:01,537
Oh, look, you brought
your friend.

422
00:24:01,539 --> 00:24:02,838
He seems glad to see me.

423
00:24:02,840 --> 00:24:04,840
He's smarter
than he looks.

424
00:24:04,842 --> 00:24:06,241
Indeed.

425
00:24:06,243 --> 00:24:10,212
Next thing I know,
he'll be quoting Shakespeare.

426
00:24:16,786 --> 00:24:19,955
Uh, please
tell your father

427
00:24:19,957 --> 00:24:23,225
to, uh, remove the shot
from the birds

428
00:24:23,227 --> 00:24:26,195
or tell your cook,
whatever you plans.

429
00:24:26,197 --> 00:24:28,230
Good day, Miss Stubbs.

430
00:24:28,232 --> 00:24:32,568
Oh, Mr. Allen,
I wish to inquire, uh...

431
00:24:33,670 --> 00:24:34,870
Father.

432
00:24:34,872 --> 00:24:37,005
A man of his word.

433
00:24:37,007 --> 00:24:39,608
Hmm. Indeed.

434
00:24:39,610 --> 00:24:42,711
Um, I was on the verge
of asking Mr. Allen

435
00:24:42,713 --> 00:24:44,079
for a guide
on the river.

436
00:24:44,081 --> 00:24:47,082
You see, Mr. Allen,
I've never seen the city

437
00:24:47,084 --> 00:24:48,550
from the perspective
of the river,

438
00:24:48,552 --> 00:24:51,086
and I'm told
it's quite beautiful.

439
00:24:51,088 --> 00:24:54,089
And Father here has
no inclination towards rowing.

440
00:24:54,091 --> 00:24:55,624
Lucy, I'm sure
Mr. Allen's time

441
00:24:55,626 --> 00:24:57,693
would be better spent
at his enterprise.

442
00:24:57,695 --> 00:24:59,595
Thanks very much,
Ward, for the duck.

443
00:24:59,597 --> 00:25:02,431
I'm sure it will
be a meal to remember.

444
00:25:02,433 --> 00:25:04,733
Well, the least
we can do then

445
00:25:04,735 --> 00:25:06,635
is invite Mr. Allen
for supper.

446
00:25:06,637 --> 00:25:07,636
Sunday? The DeSoto?

447
00:25:07,638 --> 00:25:09,138
Noon, then.

448
00:25:09,140 --> 00:25:11,707
[ door slams ]

449
00:25:11,709 --> 00:25:13,041
All right.

450
00:25:14,344 --> 00:25:19,248
[ string quartet playing ]

451
00:25:19,250 --> 00:25:22,084
WARD: Plato likens
the mind of man

452
00:25:22,086 --> 00:25:24,219
to an aviary of birds,

453
00:25:24,221 --> 00:25:27,456
and birds
to kinds of knowledge.

454
00:25:27,458 --> 00:25:30,159
I find it a queer thing,
knowledge,

455
00:25:30,161 --> 00:25:33,195
because no matter
how tight the logic,

456
00:25:33,197 --> 00:25:35,030
there's always
the errant fact,

457
00:25:35,032 --> 00:25:36,932
like... like...

458
00:25:36,934 --> 00:25:38,767
like a solitary bird,

459
00:25:38,769 --> 00:25:41,904
separated from the flock
in search of adventure.

460
00:25:41,906 --> 00:25:45,707
Are you suggesting birds
can reason?

461
00:25:47,177 --> 00:25:49,545
What is reason
next to yearning?

462
00:25:53,383 --> 00:25:57,019
Yes. Well, ahem...
tell me, Allen,

463
00:25:57,021 --> 00:26:00,088
with all this foreign education
under your belt,

464
00:26:00,090 --> 00:26:03,192
how is it you choose
to subject yourself

465
00:26:03,194 --> 00:26:05,294
to the rigors
of an outdoor life?

466
00:26:07,497 --> 00:26:10,999
Why not embrace the joys
of the airless boardroom?

467
00:26:11,001 --> 00:26:13,735
Well, the rewards are not subject
to the whims of nature.

468
00:26:13,737 --> 00:26:16,672
But instead on the whims
of man's nature.

469
00:26:16,674 --> 00:26:20,042
I find nature's nature
far more predictable

470
00:26:20,044 --> 00:26:23,378
and far more, uh, honest.

471
00:26:23,380 --> 00:26:25,714
MR. STUBBS:
Fair enough.

472
00:26:25,716 --> 00:26:26,782
Can't argue with that.

473
00:26:26,784 --> 00:26:29,451
Still, you do
seem to have a talent

474
00:26:29,453 --> 00:26:31,620
for discourse
and persuasion.

475
00:26:31,622 --> 00:26:33,922
I could see you
being very successful

476
00:26:33,924 --> 00:26:35,390
in the courtroom,
for instance.

477
00:26:35,392 --> 00:26:39,661
As a boy, I wasted
many beautiful days

478
00:26:39,663 --> 00:26:40,996
in a dusty law office,

479
00:26:40,998 --> 00:26:42,798
by arrangement
of my parents.

480
00:26:42,800 --> 00:26:45,334
They were bent on my entering
the profession.

481
00:26:45,336 --> 00:26:49,338
Following the footsteps of
the Honorable John Eliot Ward, no less?

482
00:26:49,340 --> 00:26:51,340
You seem to have
inherited from him

483
00:26:51,342 --> 00:26:54,610
a fine servant
in Christmas Moultrie.

484
00:26:58,848 --> 00:27:03,619
My uncle saw in Christmas
an accomplished guide,

485
00:27:03,621 --> 00:27:06,388
and he hired him
for his services.

486
00:27:06,390 --> 00:27:08,857
If anyone
did the inheriting,

487
00:27:08,859 --> 00:27:10,792
it was Christmas of me.

488
00:27:10,794 --> 00:27:13,729
You turn everything on its head,
don't you, Allen?

489
00:27:13,731 --> 00:27:15,163
Quite the rebel.

490
00:27:15,165 --> 00:27:17,866
And here I thought
you'd been exaggerated.

491
00:27:19,102 --> 00:27:21,336
Well, men should be
what they seem.

492
00:27:21,338 --> 00:27:24,439
Or those that be not,
would not they be none?

493
00:27:24,441 --> 00:27:27,209
Well, I think
it's absolutely delightful...

494
00:27:27,211 --> 00:27:28,710
a man of letters
who's returned to nature.

495
00:27:28,712 --> 00:27:31,713
And a sprinkle
of civil disobedience

496
00:27:31,715 --> 00:27:33,015
for good measure.

497
00:27:33,017 --> 00:27:35,384
If you are suggesting

498
00:27:35,386 --> 00:27:37,319
I'm some sort of
contemporary Thoreau,

499
00:27:37,321 --> 00:27:39,721
you are mistaken.

500
00:27:39,723 --> 00:27:41,890
I have no agenda.

501
00:27:41,892 --> 00:27:45,260
I simply prefer
this life.

502
00:27:50,166 --> 00:27:51,600
WARD: Christmas!

503
00:27:51,602 --> 00:27:54,236
The sheriff stole our order
from Ehrlich's store.

504
00:27:54,238 --> 00:27:55,637
Mr. Ward?

505
00:27:55,639 --> 00:27:57,439
I am guilty of nothing
but an honest day's work,

506
00:27:57,441 --> 00:27:59,074
while he steals a meal
right off a man's table.

507
00:27:59,076 --> 00:28:00,509
Mr. Ward!

508
00:28:00,511 --> 00:28:02,344
I have a good mind to write
the editor of the paper,

509
00:28:02,346 --> 00:28:03,879
and don't think I won't.

510
00:28:03,881 --> 00:28:05,781
[ laughing ]

511
00:28:08,084 --> 00:28:09,751
LUCY: I beg your pardon.

512
00:28:09,753 --> 00:28:12,921
I think writing
to the paper's a fine idea.

513
00:28:14,657 --> 00:28:17,859
Miss Stubbs here
hired our services.

514
00:28:20,296 --> 00:28:22,464
To do what?

515
00:28:22,466 --> 00:28:23,865
Don't worry, Mr. Allen.

516
00:28:23,867 --> 00:28:27,669
I simply wish to collect
cuttings for my garden.

517
00:28:30,206 --> 00:28:34,910
A wildflower can be cultivated
in a city garden?

518
00:28:34,912 --> 00:28:37,179
LUCY: Well,
with the right nurturing,

519
00:28:37,181 --> 00:28:39,414
most anything
can be cultivated.

520
00:28:44,287 --> 00:28:46,521
Well, I better get
these birds here

521
00:28:46,523 --> 00:28:50,192
over to the DeSoto before
the Sheriff lock them up, too.

522
00:28:50,194 --> 00:28:51,394
Yeah.

523
00:28:52,528 --> 00:28:54,329
Good afternoon,
Miss Stubbs.

524
00:28:54,331 --> 00:28:55,764
Christmas.

525
00:28:59,335 --> 00:29:00,736
[ barks ]

526
00:29:00,738 --> 00:29:02,237
[ laughs ]

527
00:29:10,279 --> 00:29:12,981
LUCY: I've seen
artists' renderings,

528
00:29:12,983 --> 00:29:15,050
but I had no idea.

529
00:29:15,052 --> 00:29:18,653
It's like floating
on a sea of stars.

530
00:29:20,923 --> 00:29:22,691
And that perfume.

531
00:29:22,693 --> 00:29:23,759
[ sniffs ]

532
00:29:23,761 --> 00:29:24,659
Mmm.

533
00:29:24,661 --> 00:29:27,362
It's like
stars made of sugar.

534
00:29:29,332 --> 00:29:31,466
Starry archipelagoes...

535
00:29:36,773 --> 00:29:37,973
raving skies.

536
00:29:37,975 --> 00:29:39,674
[ laughs ] Yes.

537
00:29:39,676 --> 00:29:41,510
Raving skies.

538
00:29:42,879 --> 00:29:45,847
My father built a solarium
for my garden.

539
00:29:45,849 --> 00:29:49,951
When I was a little girl,
I couldn't be outside,

540
00:29:49,953 --> 00:29:54,122
and the solarium seemed
impossibly large to fill,

541
00:29:54,124 --> 00:29:55,891
but I filled it
till bursting.

542
00:29:55,893 --> 00:29:58,627
And when there was
no more room for planting,

543
00:29:58,629 --> 00:30:02,297
I laid down
in the middle of the floor,

544
00:30:02,299 --> 00:30:04,399
buried beneath the flowers

545
00:30:04,401 --> 00:30:07,002
and imagined
I was flying.

546
00:30:11,140 --> 00:30:13,408
A flying carpet.

547
00:30:13,410 --> 00:30:16,711
You know
Vasnetsov's painting?

548
00:30:16,713 --> 00:30:18,113
Yeah.

549
00:30:18,115 --> 00:30:19,514
Oh.

550
00:30:19,516 --> 00:30:21,516
My father knew
the Russian Ambassador.

551
00:30:21,518 --> 00:30:24,719
He described it
in such vivid detail,

552
00:30:24,721 --> 00:30:28,690
I felt like I'd seen it
with my own two eyes.

553
00:30:28,692 --> 00:30:31,359
Well, now, you must have known
the Russian Ambassador.

554
00:30:31,361 --> 00:30:33,028
Father says
you were in Russia?

555
00:30:34,497 --> 00:30:38,400
Oh, the first time I disappeared
beneath the flowers,

556
00:30:38,402 --> 00:30:39,935
my parents
couldn't find me.

557
00:30:39,937 --> 00:30:42,938
Well, Father nearly had
a heart attack, but...

558
00:30:42,940 --> 00:30:46,508
He'd spent my whole life
trying to protect me

559
00:30:46,510 --> 00:30:48,310
from all kinds
of imagined horrors,

560
00:30:48,312 --> 00:30:52,481
and there I had vanished
into thin air.

561
00:30:53,616 --> 00:30:55,717
It was my refuge.

562
00:30:57,053 --> 00:30:59,421
[ thunder ]

563
00:31:08,531 --> 00:31:11,032
[ ducks quacking, splashing ]

564
00:31:17,807 --> 00:31:20,075
If I were a bird,
you wouldn't catch me.

565
00:31:21,477 --> 00:31:24,913
You see, I recognize
a decoy when I see one.

566
00:31:28,451 --> 00:31:31,419
So, what kind of bird
would I be?

567
00:31:32,889 --> 00:31:35,390
Uh, I beg your pardon?

568
00:31:35,392 --> 00:31:37,325
If I were a bird
and you were hunting me,

569
00:31:37,327 --> 00:31:38,793
what would I be?

570
00:31:40,062 --> 00:31:41,530
Well?

571
00:31:45,368 --> 00:31:47,102
A mallard.

572
00:31:48,404 --> 00:31:52,941
Particularly
beautiful bird in flight.

573
00:31:52,943 --> 00:31:55,410
That's all? Just a bunch
of pretty feathers?

574
00:31:55,412 --> 00:31:56,578
Oh, no.

575
00:31:56,580 --> 00:32:00,849
I enjoy a bird
that uses its, uh,

576
00:32:00,851 --> 00:32:03,118
native cunning
to outwit the hunter.

577
00:32:05,154 --> 00:32:07,055
A mallard has canny.

578
00:32:09,125 --> 00:32:11,192
I see.
Mmm.

579
00:32:11,194 --> 00:32:12,827
Hmm...

580
00:32:12,829 --> 00:32:16,164
There's some meaning
in it, I think.

581
00:32:16,166 --> 00:32:19,701
I don't know if I can put
my finger on it, but...

582
00:32:21,737 --> 00:32:25,340
sometimes I feel
as if I'm up there,

583
00:32:25,342 --> 00:32:27,275
pulling toward some...

584
00:32:30,613 --> 00:32:32,180
distant purpose.

585
00:32:38,154 --> 00:32:40,055
Teach me to shoot.

586
00:32:40,057 --> 00:32:41,489
What?

587
00:32:41,491 --> 00:32:44,059
Not a bird, a...
a target.

588
00:32:44,061 --> 00:32:46,995
That old barge over there,
is it loaded?

589
00:32:46,997 --> 00:32:48,396
Of course, it is.
Careful, now...

590
00:32:48,398 --> 00:32:49,631
[ gunshot ] Oh!

591
00:32:50,566 --> 00:32:51,900
[ gasps ]

592
00:32:51,902 --> 00:32:53,835
[ shouting ]

593
00:32:53,837 --> 00:32:57,606
Uh... Here!
Grab this, here!

594
00:32:59,475 --> 00:33:01,209
Grab it.

595
00:33:01,211 --> 00:33:02,444
Grab the gun.

596
00:33:02,446 --> 00:33:04,379
Hold on.

597
00:33:04,381 --> 00:33:06,948
Good. Good.

598
00:33:06,950 --> 00:33:08,850
[ laughing ]
You can't swim.

599
00:33:08,852 --> 00:33:12,220
Don't worry,
it'll be our secret.

600
00:33:12,222 --> 00:33:14,589
It's not a secret.

601
00:33:14,591 --> 00:33:16,958
It's just not
a publicized fact.

602
00:33:16,960 --> 00:33:19,260
Oh, well, hmm...

603
00:33:19,262 --> 00:33:22,130
Truth hath
a quiet breast.

604
00:33:24,800 --> 00:33:27,268
You're a rare man,
Ward Allen.

605
00:33:27,270 --> 00:33:33,608
And while I do find your word play
entertaining to a point,

606
00:33:33,610 --> 00:33:36,111
I'm not a patient woman.

607
00:33:36,113 --> 00:33:37,679
Can you remember that?

608
00:33:42,618 --> 00:33:44,119
I will.

609
00:33:47,089 --> 00:33:50,125
Can you remember
not to touch my guns?

610
00:33:52,895 --> 00:33:54,129
Yes, I can.

611
00:33:56,465 --> 00:33:58,700
Okay, then.

612
00:33:59,969 --> 00:34:01,603
Yes.

613
00:34:06,375 --> 00:34:08,710
I've made
my decision, Father.

614
00:34:08,712 --> 00:34:10,178
[ clock chiming ]

615
00:34:10,180 --> 00:34:13,248
You've ruined
so many prospects, Lucy.

616
00:34:13,250 --> 00:34:15,316
Hmm.
Nothing but boys,

617
00:34:15,318 --> 00:34:17,819
following
in their father's footsteps.

618
00:34:17,821 --> 00:34:20,255
I'd know my life
before I had even lived it.

619
00:34:20,257 --> 00:34:21,856
The man's a boor.

620
00:34:21,858 --> 00:34:25,093
Ward Allen walked away from
a fine inheritance.

621
00:34:25,095 --> 00:34:26,295
God knows why.

622
00:34:26,296 --> 00:34:27,429
He wanted to be free.

623
00:34:27,431 --> 00:34:28,430
Free?

624
00:34:28,432 --> 00:34:29,431
His Negro's free.

625
00:34:29,433 --> 00:34:30,565
Father!

626
00:34:30,567 --> 00:34:32,901
Lucy,
don't say anymore.

627
00:34:32,903 --> 00:34:36,071
Let's talk this over
while we're away this summer.

628
00:34:36,073 --> 00:34:38,573
I won't be accompanying you
to the Vineyard, Mother.

629
00:34:42,545 --> 00:34:46,047
I am neither yours
to dispense nor to withhold.

630
00:34:48,651 --> 00:34:52,187
[ footsteps withdrawing ]

631
00:34:57,793 --> 00:35:00,128
[ coins and jewelry
clattering on table ]

632
00:36:31,320 --> 00:36:32,754
[ chuckles ]

633
00:37:08,691 --> 00:37:09,824
[ gunshot ]
[ gasps ]

634
00:37:09,826 --> 00:37:11,392
WARD:
Hyah hyah hyah!

635
00:37:11,394 --> 00:37:13,661
Aah!

636
00:37:13,663 --> 00:37:14,662
[ man gasping ]

637
00:37:14,664 --> 00:37:15,697
[ gunshot ]

638
00:37:15,699 --> 00:37:16,899
Mrs. Ward Allen!

639
00:37:18,334 --> 00:37:20,435
[ gunshot ]

640
00:37:20,437 --> 00:37:23,338
Your beauty startles
the night!

641
00:37:23,340 --> 00:37:28,843
I shall make a quick loop
around the Earth and return!

642
00:37:28,845 --> 00:37:29,844
Prepare!
Don't you dare!

643
00:37:29,846 --> 00:37:31,212
[ gunshot ]

644
00:37:31,214 --> 00:37:33,715
Eat no onions nor garlic...
Stop that man!

645
00:37:33,717 --> 00:37:35,149
for we are to utter sweet breath.
[ lamp shatters ]

646
00:37:35,151 --> 00:37:37,252
I will, soon as he
stops shootin'.

647
00:37:37,254 --> 00:37:38,486
[ gunshot ]

648
00:37:38,488 --> 00:37:39,487
[ gasps ]
[ horse neighs ]

649
00:37:39,489 --> 00:37:40,922
WARD: Make way!

650
00:37:40,924 --> 00:37:43,191
Hyah hyah hyah hyah!

651
00:37:47,263 --> 00:37:49,197
MAN: They should be
there waiting for us.

652
00:37:50,199 --> 00:37:52,500
Much obliged
for the sleep, Officer.

653
00:37:52,502 --> 00:37:54,035
My pleasure, Ward.

654
00:37:54,037 --> 00:37:55,770
Hope the little lady's
ready to receive you.

655
00:37:55,772 --> 00:37:58,740
You know, a woman ain't
an argument to win, don't you?

656
00:37:58,742 --> 00:38:01,643
One of these decoys here
ain't gonna bring Miss Lucy in.

657
00:38:01,645 --> 00:38:06,180
Ah, but for thy sweet understanding,
Christmas, a woman.

658
00:38:06,182 --> 00:38:08,082
You're a perfect beast!

659
00:38:10,786 --> 00:38:12,420
Lucy.

660
00:38:13,455 --> 00:38:15,523
Lucy?

661
00:38:15,525 --> 00:38:17,191
Lucy, let me in!

662
00:38:17,193 --> 00:38:18,626
You can sleep
with the dog!

663
00:38:18,628 --> 00:38:19,994
That's where you belong!

664
00:38:19,996 --> 00:38:21,195
It's Rock you
should have betrothed!

665
00:38:21,197 --> 00:38:22,397
[ dog whines ]

666
00:38:23,599 --> 00:38:26,267
Please, my dear,
at least let me in

667
00:38:26,269 --> 00:38:28,503
behind the privacy
of closed doors.

668
00:38:28,505 --> 00:38:29,938
Privacy?
Mm-hmm.

669
00:38:29,940 --> 00:38:32,040
Do you think there's
a soul in Savannah

670
00:38:32,042 --> 00:38:33,474
that doesn't know
you left my side

671
00:38:33,476 --> 00:38:34,542
in the middle
of the night

672
00:38:34,544 --> 00:38:36,010
to wallow
in a vat of whiskey?

673
00:38:37,646 --> 00:38:40,148
Now, Lucy...

674
00:38:42,885 --> 00:38:44,485
You're right.

675
00:38:47,990 --> 00:38:51,392
I... I temper myself
to keep my temper,

676
00:38:51,394 --> 00:38:54,595
and if I need to water
myself down at times,

677
00:38:54,597 --> 00:38:58,866
well, admit it.

678
00:38:58,868 --> 00:39:01,736
A smaller man could never hold
your interest.

679
00:39:01,738 --> 00:39:03,371
[ sighs ]

680
00:39:07,409 --> 00:39:10,011
As I am, I adore you.

681
00:39:10,013 --> 00:39:12,246
How well you show it.

682
00:39:17,252 --> 00:39:20,855
What would you
have me do, hmm?

683
00:39:21,857 --> 00:39:23,925
What would you
have me do?

684
00:39:25,060 --> 00:39:28,863
To gild refined gold,

685
00:39:28,865 --> 00:39:30,231
to paint the lily...

686
00:39:32,968 --> 00:39:35,169
to throw perfume
on the violet...

687
00:39:37,272 --> 00:39:40,141
to add another hue
into the rainbow.

688
00:39:41,176 --> 00:39:42,276
Mm.

689
00:39:42,278 --> 00:39:45,947
Wasteful
and ridiculous...

690
00:39:50,152 --> 00:39:51,419
excess.

691
00:39:58,427 --> 00:40:00,428
[ whines ]

692
00:40:07,302 --> 00:40:10,038
CHRISTMAS: ♪ It's cold

693
00:40:11,240 --> 00:40:13,541
♪ It's cold

694
00:40:13,543 --> 00:40:16,577
♪ Now I lost my lover

695
00:40:18,881 --> 00:40:20,948
♪ It's cold

696
00:40:20,950 --> 00:40:23,151
♪ It's cold

697
00:40:24,219 --> 00:40:29,390
♪ And where
shall I find her? ♪

698
00:40:30,492 --> 00:40:31,692
WARD: Heh.

699
00:40:33,095 --> 00:40:35,596
Pardon the tardiness,
Mr. Moultrie.

700
00:40:37,199 --> 00:40:39,901
Late's still better
than never, Mr. Ward.

701
00:40:39,903 --> 00:40:42,503
[ song begins ]

702
00:40:46,241 --> 00:40:47,575
♪ Bring me a gator

703
00:40:47,577 --> 00:40:50,344
♪ Girl, when you
get off the island ♪

704
00:40:50,346 --> 00:40:53,081
♪ A ringtail 'ator

705
00:40:53,083 --> 00:40:54,549
♪ Oh, when you get
off the island ♪

706
00:40:54,551 --> 00:40:56,050
Clear.

707
00:40:56,052 --> 00:40:58,119
♪ A Darien gator

708
00:40:58,121 --> 00:41:00,588
♪ Girl, when you get
off the island ♪

709
00:41:00,590 --> 00:41:04,692
♪ Ohh, when you get
off the island ♪

710
00:41:04,694 --> 00:41:05,793
All right, that's it.

711
00:41:05,795 --> 00:41:07,328
That's
the last of them.

712
00:41:07,330 --> 00:41:10,598
That's 10 for Ehrlich's,
20 for the DeSoto.

713
00:41:10,600 --> 00:41:11,566
Uh-huh.

714
00:41:11,568 --> 00:41:12,834
That's
almost a quarter.

715
00:41:12,836 --> 00:41:14,469
[ gunshot ]

716
00:41:14,471 --> 00:41:15,870
WARD: What the hell
was that?

717
00:41:15,872 --> 00:41:17,371
It's Old Man Lynah!

718
00:41:17,373 --> 00:41:19,006
Ain't I tell you not
to get on his property?

719
00:41:19,008 --> 00:41:20,942
[ laughing ] Oh, sh...

720
00:41:20,944 --> 00:41:22,009
Ho!

721
00:41:22,011 --> 00:41:23,277
[ gunshot ]

722
00:41:23,279 --> 00:41:24,879
CHRISTMAS: He knows
it's us, Mr. Ward!

723
00:41:24,881 --> 00:41:27,081
Well, if he knows it's us,
why is he shootin'?

724
00:41:27,083 --> 00:41:28,983
He's mad about you
hitchin' up

725
00:41:28,985 --> 00:41:30,284
with Miss Lucy,
that's why.

726
00:41:30,286 --> 00:41:32,787
[ laughing ]
I did that man a favor.

727
00:41:32,789 --> 00:41:34,222
Lucy'd eat
his boy for lunch.

728
00:41:34,224 --> 00:41:35,790
All the same,
he all worked up,

729
00:41:35,792 --> 00:41:37,625
and you the best one
to blame!

730
00:41:37,627 --> 00:41:39,160
WARD:
This is ridiculous.

731
00:41:39,162 --> 00:41:40,328
Let's get out of here.

732
00:41:40,330 --> 00:41:44,632
Mr. Lynah, uh... truce!

733
00:41:44,634 --> 00:41:46,334
Truce.

734
00:41:46,336 --> 00:41:48,536
We'll just-
We'll be on our way.

735
00:41:48,538 --> 00:41:51,372
Rock! Here!

736
00:41:51,374 --> 00:41:53,708
Yeah. We'll... We'll
be on out of here.

737
00:41:53,710 --> 00:41:55,443
Here! Go on up!

738
00:41:57,980 --> 00:42:00,014
WARD: Here. Here.

739
00:42:00,016 --> 00:42:02,383
Come! Sit. Come here.

740
00:42:06,488 --> 00:42:08,256
[ dog whines ]

741
00:42:08,258 --> 00:42:09,824
Here!

742
00:42:09,826 --> 00:42:13,361
Christmas, you haven't
said a word since Lynah's.

743
00:42:14,730 --> 00:42:15,897
No, sir.

744
00:42:15,899 --> 00:42:17,231
Why?

745
00:42:17,233 --> 00:42:18,499
I got nothin'
to say, sir.

746
00:42:18,501 --> 00:42:19,600
Since when?

747
00:42:19,602 --> 00:42:21,402
All I'm saying is,

748
00:42:21,404 --> 00:42:23,504
it would have been
different it was just me.

749
00:42:28,143 --> 00:42:30,811
You still mad
about that?

750
00:42:30,813 --> 00:42:33,147
All I'm for saying is.

751
00:42:34,750 --> 00:42:36,317
Listen up now.

752
00:42:37,953 --> 00:42:39,387
Lynah was aiming
to hit me,

753
00:42:39,389 --> 00:42:40,788
and every man
around here

754
00:42:40,790 --> 00:42:44,058
has a right to defend
his own property.

755
00:42:44,060 --> 00:42:45,693
All right, then.

756
00:42:46,728 --> 00:42:48,429
Afternoon, Mr. Ward.

757
00:42:48,431 --> 00:42:50,097
Hey.

758
00:42:50,099 --> 00:42:52,567
It is an absolute
preposterous statement

759
00:42:52,569 --> 00:42:53,768
the outcome would
have been different

760
00:42:53,770 --> 00:42:55,002
had I not been there.

761
00:42:55,004 --> 00:42:58,439
Lynah was aimed
to shoot me, all right?

762
00:42:58,441 --> 00:43:00,675
He missed
and we got away!

763
00:43:00,677 --> 00:43:02,310
No, sir, you got away!

764
00:43:02,312 --> 00:43:04,178
I just be along there
with you like the dog here!

765
00:43:04,180 --> 00:43:05,346
Well,
if I hadn't been there,

766
00:43:05,348 --> 00:43:06,380
he wouldn't
have chased Rock

767
00:43:06,382 --> 00:43:07,615
down the river
and killed him!

768
00:43:07,617 --> 00:43:09,684
No, sir, he would
have let your dog live!

769
00:43:09,686 --> 00:43:13,721
[ people murmuring ]

770
00:43:13,723 --> 00:43:15,256
All I'm sa...

771
00:43:18,660 --> 00:43:21,596
Your world ain't mine,
you understand?

772
00:43:26,301 --> 00:43:29,203
Can I be of any assistance,
Mr. Allen?

773
00:43:41,049 --> 00:43:42,850
WARD: Gimme a whiskey.

774
00:43:55,897 --> 00:43:57,565
[ door closes ]

775
00:43:57,567 --> 00:43:59,800
[ footsteps ]

776
00:44:55,991 --> 00:44:57,825
[ dog barking ]

777
00:45:00,696 --> 00:45:02,363
[ gunshots ]

778
00:45:27,889 --> 00:45:29,089
[ spits ]

779
00:45:30,192 --> 00:45:32,626
Why do you hunt, sir?

780
00:45:32,628 --> 00:45:34,795
It's a gentleman's sport.

781
00:45:36,832 --> 00:45:39,233
Makes you feel sporty,
does it, huh,

782
00:45:39,235 --> 00:45:40,968
to shoot a bird or two?

783
00:45:45,907 --> 00:45:48,576
Do you know these birds?

784
00:45:48,578 --> 00:45:51,212
Can you tell a canvasback
from a widgeon

785
00:45:51,214 --> 00:45:52,747
from the way it turns
in the air,

786
00:45:52,749 --> 00:45:53,848
from how it feeds?

787
00:45:53,850 --> 00:45:56,117
Do you know
the journeys they take,

788
00:45:56,119 --> 00:45:59,086
their determination,
power of will

789
00:45:59,088 --> 00:46:00,488
wrapped up in
that small little breast

790
00:46:00,490 --> 00:46:02,623
you fill so carelessly
with shot?

791
00:46:02,625 --> 00:46:03,758
Do you?

792
00:46:03,760 --> 00:46:07,328
Listen to you,
the original noble savage.

793
00:46:07,330 --> 00:46:09,730
You know nothin',

794
00:46:09,732 --> 00:46:12,466
and you think
about nothin'.

795
00:46:12,468 --> 00:46:15,903
200 taken my way
is an honest act.

796
00:46:15,905 --> 00:46:17,338
It is a transaction

797
00:46:17,340 --> 00:46:19,540
as old as
our two species.

798
00:46:19,542 --> 00:46:21,442
See, I know what I do.

799
00:46:23,745 --> 00:46:25,813
Two single birds
taken your way,

800
00:46:25,815 --> 00:46:28,315
now, that's what
I call a slaughter.

801
00:46:31,186 --> 00:46:33,020
[ groaning ]

802
00:46:52,240 --> 00:46:54,275
A gun room
has guns in it!

803
00:46:54,277 --> 00:46:56,710
And a home
has a husband in it.

804
00:47:09,724 --> 00:47:11,425
[ door closes ]

805
00:47:24,706 --> 00:47:27,908
CHRISTMAS: Mr. John says
you was worrisome.

806
00:47:31,580 --> 00:47:34,949
WARD: What else did my uncle say,
Mr. Moultrie?

807
00:47:36,518 --> 00:47:39,520
Call me Christmas
that's all.

808
00:47:42,157 --> 00:47:43,557
Christmas.

809
00:48:02,043 --> 00:48:04,778
Well, Mr. John say they won't take
the summer duck.

810
00:48:05,947 --> 00:48:08,782
Oh, hell will freeze over
before they take mine.

811
00:48:08,784 --> 00:48:11,852
I'll take it all the way
to the Supreme Court if I have to.

812
00:48:16,291 --> 00:48:18,926
Young blood doth not obey
an old decree.

813
00:48:22,464 --> 00:48:25,699
We cannot cross the cause
why we were born.

814
00:49:30,732 --> 00:49:33,067
[ car sputtering ]

815
00:49:51,319 --> 00:49:55,055
[ men conversing
indistinctly ]

816
00:50:49,811 --> 00:50:52,079
Well, Mr. Judge,
the alligator got no limit,

817
00:50:52,081 --> 00:50:54,815
and the raccoon
ain't got no limit,

818
00:50:54,817 --> 00:50:56,684
so why should Christmas
have a limit?

819
00:50:56,686 --> 00:50:58,919
JUDGE HARDEN: Well, this
is serious, Christmas.

820
00:50:58,921 --> 00:51:02,656
Repeated probationary sentences
cannot be supported.

821
00:51:02,658 --> 00:51:05,693
Sir, Warden Rossignol
clearly states

822
00:51:05,695 --> 00:51:07,628
that he identified me

823
00:51:07,630 --> 00:51:10,964
at the distance
of 200 yards at sunset.

824
00:51:10,966 --> 00:51:13,567
PROSECUTOR: Your Honor,
this is a matter of undisputed fact.

825
00:51:13,569 --> 00:51:14,935
WARD:
Excuse me, Your Honor,

826
00:51:14,937 --> 00:51:18,138
but the undisputed facts
are these.

827
00:51:18,140 --> 00:51:20,674
200 yards, sunset,

828
00:51:20,676 --> 00:51:24,278
saw grass this time
of year this high.

829
00:51:24,280 --> 00:51:25,879
Person firing at ducks,

830
00:51:25,881 --> 00:51:28,849
who must have stood at least
this deep in the mire,

831
00:51:28,851 --> 00:51:30,651
meaning that
at 200 yards,

832
00:51:30,653 --> 00:51:32,820
Warden Rossignol
might deduce

833
00:51:32,822 --> 00:51:35,289
what species of God's creation
fired the gun,

834
00:51:35,291 --> 00:51:37,825
but would not have been
able to sex the shooter,

835
00:51:37,827 --> 00:51:41,195
much less identify
him... or her.

836
00:51:41,197 --> 00:51:42,463
[ laughter ]

837
00:51:42,465 --> 00:51:45,632
Or anyone for that matter
who owns a shotgun in the county.

838
00:51:45,634 --> 00:51:48,001
[ laughter ]

839
00:51:48,803 --> 00:51:51,238
By the way, Your Honor,
you still own that Greener?

840
00:51:51,240 --> 00:51:53,273
Yes, I do.

841
00:51:53,275 --> 00:51:55,609
WARD: Yeah, it's
beautifully made, isn't it?

842
00:51:55,611 --> 00:51:57,377
Oh, yes.

843
00:51:57,379 --> 00:51:59,546
If the English made kings
the way they made guns,

844
00:51:59,548 --> 00:52:01,115
we'd still be a colony.

845
00:52:01,117 --> 00:52:02,516
[ laughter ]

846
00:52:02,518 --> 00:52:03,951
Your Honor!

847
00:52:03,953 --> 00:52:05,419
Of course, of course.

848
00:52:05,421 --> 00:52:06,754
Uh, of course.

849
00:52:06,756 --> 00:52:09,490
Uh, Christmas, uh,

850
00:52:09,492 --> 00:52:14,995
you knew it was against the law
to shoot summer duck.

851
00:52:14,997 --> 00:52:17,097
Yes, sir.

852
00:52:17,099 --> 00:52:23,003
Well, Christmas, why then did
you not dispose of the ducks?

853
00:52:26,941 --> 00:52:28,675
Sir?

854
00:52:28,677 --> 00:52:30,677
What I mean is, Christmas,

855
00:52:30,679 --> 00:52:32,279
when you saw
the warden coming,

856
00:52:32,281 --> 00:52:35,916
why didn't you throw away
the summer duck?

857
00:52:38,052 --> 00:52:40,788
Mr. Judge, you must
never et a summer duck.

858
00:52:40,790 --> 00:52:42,823
[ laughter ]

859
00:52:46,861 --> 00:52:48,595
JUDGE HARDEN:
Case dismissed.

860
00:52:48,597 --> 00:52:52,833
[ laughter and applause ]

861
00:53:27,368 --> 00:53:29,303
Well, go on, open it.

862
00:53:48,122 --> 00:53:51,859
You've nothing left to prove
with guns and bluster, Ward.

863
00:53:53,428 --> 00:53:55,796
Try a different weapon.

864
00:54:37,205 --> 00:54:38,405
[ scoffs ]

865
00:55:49,010 --> 00:55:53,213
[ machinery ]

866
00:55:53,215 --> 00:55:55,549
CHRISTMAS: They're
building a new factory.

867
00:55:57,151 --> 00:55:59,219
Imperial.

868
00:56:00,688 --> 00:56:02,622
Imperial, my ass.

869
00:56:04,292 --> 00:56:07,894
They cleared all
but that patch over there.

870
00:56:07,896 --> 00:56:11,098
The boss man's
new hunting ground.

871
00:56:14,168 --> 00:56:16,136
What kind of fool
thinks a duck,

872
00:56:16,138 --> 00:56:20,540
with all the low country
from here to the Everglades,

873
00:56:20,542 --> 00:56:23,543
is gonna fly
in that concrete patch?

874
00:56:26,714 --> 00:56:28,982
It's no good here.

875
00:56:30,084 --> 00:56:33,387
Hey. Wh... where's Rock?

876
00:56:33,389 --> 00:56:35,055
Rock!

877
00:56:37,558 --> 00:56:38,692
Last I seen him,

878
00:56:38,694 --> 00:56:41,528
he was over
by that tree there.

879
00:57:31,612 --> 00:57:33,146
Mr. Ward...

880
00:57:35,316 --> 00:57:38,051
Rock always done
us his best.

881
00:57:39,620 --> 00:57:43,156
Now he done his last.

882
00:57:43,158 --> 00:57:47,961
Shakespeare could not
have said it better, Christmas.

883
00:58:08,616 --> 00:58:10,650
[ fingers tapping ]

884
00:58:28,369 --> 00:58:33,707
WARD: "How a Duck Hunter
Avoids Being a Sinner."

885
00:58:38,412 --> 00:58:40,147
JACK: Oh, did
I tell you I found

886
00:58:40,149 --> 00:58:42,649
some of Ward's
newspaper articles?

887
00:58:42,651 --> 00:58:44,751
Listen to this.

888
00:58:44,753 --> 00:58:48,855
Called "How the Duck Hunter
Avoids Being a Sinner."

889
00:58:48,857 --> 00:58:50,690
"With all sorts
of unreasonable

890
00:58:50,692 --> 00:58:53,426
"and absurd restrictions
on duck shootin' now,

891
00:58:53,428 --> 00:58:55,595
"fella can't go out
in the short open season

892
00:58:55,597 --> 00:58:59,266
"without transgressing
some of the fool don'ts.

893
00:58:59,268 --> 00:59:02,169
"So the safest way
to avoid being a sinner

894
00:59:02,171 --> 00:59:04,471
"when a fella
goes duck shootin',

895
00:59:04,473 --> 00:59:06,673
is not to shoot
anything at all".

896
00:59:06,675 --> 00:59:09,176
[ laughing ]

897
00:59:10,278 --> 00:59:12,946
Yeah, Ward was prolific.

898
00:59:12,948 --> 00:59:15,248
Holding back the tide

899
00:59:15,250 --> 00:59:19,219
with that fountain pen
Lucy gave him.

900
00:59:19,221 --> 00:59:20,421
Yeah.
Trying to, anyway.

901
00:59:20,422 --> 00:59:22,389
Everybody's emptying
out their attics

902
00:59:22,391 --> 00:59:24,558
for Lila's
historical society.

903
00:59:24,560 --> 00:59:27,928
Homer built her,
got to be 200 crates.

904
00:59:27,930 --> 00:59:29,663
Won't take a nickel
for them.

905
00:59:29,665 --> 00:59:31,665
Homer's daddy the same.

906
00:59:31,667 --> 00:59:35,235
Settled Ward's account
for a couple of old guns.

907
00:59:35,237 --> 00:59:40,173
You know, my daddy was
on the search party found Ward's body.

908
00:59:40,175 --> 00:59:44,010
Said he found him in...
wearing his pajamas.

909
00:59:44,012 --> 00:59:47,881
Some say
it wasn't an accident.

910
00:59:47,883 --> 00:59:49,616
What is?

911
00:59:51,519 --> 00:59:54,254
Yeah.

912
00:59:54,256 --> 00:59:57,490
Well, whatever it is
Ward was searching for...

913
00:59:57,492 --> 00:59:58,792
[ chuckles ]

914
00:59:58,794 --> 01:00:00,694
it eluded him.

915
01:00:02,463 --> 01:00:07,334
Might as well add that
to your collection.

916
01:00:16,677 --> 01:00:18,812
Christmas, I...

917
01:00:18,814 --> 01:00:20,747
I found you
a place to live.

918
01:00:21,882 --> 01:00:23,617
It's comfortable.

919
01:00:24,819 --> 01:00:27,988
It's not home,
but I made sure of it.

920
01:00:27,990 --> 01:00:31,191
You're gonna be
comfortable.

921
01:00:39,033 --> 01:00:40,600
All right.

922
